{"add":{"doc":{"id":"0317b5694b5782c5d3f60e07d29bad8003cbfc9fdc054c81d07cd44dbe4e3935","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/ae/HEARST2.JPG/220px-HEARST2.JPG","previous":[],"after":["Searching for an occupation, in 1887 Hearst took over management of a newspaper, the San Francisco Examiner, which his father received in 1880 as repayment for a gambling debt.[8] Giving his paper a grand motto, \"Monarch of the Dailies,\" he acquired the best equipment and the most talented writers of the time, including Ambrose Bierce, Mark Twain, Jack London, and political cartoonist Homer Davenport. A self-proclaimed populist, Hearst went on to publish stories of municipal and financial corruption, often attacking companies in which his own family held an interest. Within a few years, his paper dominated the San Francisco market."]}}}